Furthermore, most men interviewed were dissatisfied with their current work situation and most desired to obtain steady and stable work, higher incomes, and a more formal employment situation.
Conceptualisation
Interviewees reflected a variety of gender ideals that balanced traditional gender social norms with perspectives on modernism that acknowledged and craved changes. This complex gender ideology demonstrates the theoreticalunderpinnings of this project. As stated previously, multiple gender ideologies exist in the society and the ideal type is produced by looking at the saliency and degree of social ascendancy that gender has been conferred. This project has focused on the findings for the hegemonic7 gender role type to explain these gender ideals and understands what the various gender roles are, how Cape Verdeans internalise them, how they behave and react to them, and their implications. These traditional gender role social norms for men were often internalised by the Balanta adults in the Cape Verdean GQA sample; however, these beliefs were not always acted9 upon. For example, males in this society engage in polygamy and often are unfaithful in relationships10. Although these behaviours are societal taboos, many of the men interviewed consider these traditional gender roles descriptive of cultural ideal.
